<paragraph id="8BE81445FFEFC86CFF5DBBA4FDC0FDBB" blockId="17.[151,1437,150,609]" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">
<taxonomicName id="4C576FC6FFEFC86CFF5DBBA4FE99FDC3" baseAuthorityName="Huckett" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[199,328,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setibasis">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFEFC86CFF5DBBA4FE99FDC3" box="[199,328,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">D. setibasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare species in 
<collectingCountry id="F34054D5FFEFC86CFD84BBA4FDAFFDC3" box="[542,638,511,537]" name="Armenia" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">Armenia</collectingCountry>
and was previously found only in 
<collectingRegion id="4993DAA7FFEFC86CFC66BBA4FB0DFDC3" box="[1020,1244,511,537]" country="Armenia" name="Aragatsotn" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">Aragatsotn province</collectingRegion>
at Lake Kari and on Mt Aragats, from 
<quantity id="4CAFB9A0FFEFC86CFEE0B878FDF4FDE7" box="[378,549,546,573]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.375" metricValueMax="3.56" metricValueMin="3.19" pageId="17" pageNumber="372" unit="m" value="3375.0" valueMax="3560.0" valueMin="3190.0">3190 to 3560 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC669B4FFEFC86CFDA8B878FD1FFDE7" author="Pont, A. C." box="[562,718,546,573]" pageId="17" pageNumber="372" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref13937" refString="Pont, A. C. (2018) The Muscidae (Diptera) of Armenia. Zootaxa, 4465 (1), 1 - 69. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4465.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Pont 2018: 15</bibRefCitation>
). It is clearly a high-altitude species in both 
<collectingCountry id="F34054D5FFEFC86CFB33B878FAD8FDE7" box="[1193,1289,547,573]" name="Armenia" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">Armenia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F34054D5FFEFC86CFAA7B878FA49FDE7" box="[1341,1432,547,573]" name="Georgia" pageId="17" pageNumber="372">Georgia</collectingCountry>
, occurring well above the tree-line.
</paragraph>
